What children taught in public schools these days don&#39;t know no longer
surprises me.  I just responded to a person on the Shavian site who was
making the argument that everyone used computers and no one wrote
anymore.  So why is Wal-mart still selling dozens of different pens,
markers and pencils?  Presumably, these kids who can&#39;t write in cursive
are able to print?  The whole point of cursive is that it is faster than
printing as it doesn&#39;t require penlifts between letters.  Quikscript has
the advantage of cursive in that most letters can be connected, but it
is easier to read than cursive because the letters shapes are not
altered by ligatures.  QS can also function as a shorthand for taking
notes in school.  The student should have a better chance of keeping up
with the teacher.

Paige

&quot;I despise a world which does not feel that music is a higher revelation
than all wisdom and philosophy.&quot; 
-Ludwig van Beethoven 

-----Original Message-----
From: Wayne Cornelius [mailto:wayne_cornelius@...] 
Sent: Sunday, February 20, 2005 2:22 PM
To: Read_Alphabet@yahoogroups.com
Subject: [Read_Alphabet] The demise of cursive handwriting



This may not be a useful topic for the Quikscript forum -- but if 
anyone uses Quikscript to communicate with others&quot; [see the new 
poll], it seems germane. Earlier this month, a staff writer in the 
Raleigh NC newspaper wrote a story that cursive handwriting (as a 
subject taught to school children) seems to be fading away. Students 
use keyboards to do much of their writing. Often, homework 
assignments are required to be typed, not written; and assignments 
may be turned in using email. (Census surveys show that 70 percent of 
homes now have computers.) The teaching of handwriting has become 
inconsistent. Students eventually discover that they don&#39;t *need to 
use* cursive writing for much of anything except checkwriting & 
signing legal documents. A local middle school teacher stopped 
writing notes in cursive on her whiteboard 3 years ago because every 
class she teaches has students who don&#39;t know how to read it. 
(Copyrighted article on newsobserver.com; I can send a link to it 
later if someone asks for it.)

Do you think Quikscript would have anything helpful to offer for this 
problem? 










